<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
There are valid reasons for at least adding the /pet no attack command.  <P>The margin for error between 55-60 is razor thin.  One broken mez means you all die as a party even if you were doing great up until that point.  Your pets act like wet tissue paper as far as how long they can delay a mobs before dieing at this level.<P>And while your enchanter can stun and mes a mob your pet is engaged with it's still not assured he'll get it the mob on the first attempt while you back off and move your pet to a safe distance.<P>You can midigate pet control concerns and limit thier impact by smart play but can't eliminate them.<P>-not sending a pet until everything is mezed<BR>-not sitting when pulls come in<BR>-move pet and yourself as far from the multiple mobs as possible so loose swings don't agro your pet.<BR>-keeping a tight vigil on your pet<BR>-know the bad pathing areas and how your pet will behave around them<BR>-don't let your pet chase mobs<BR>....<P>The list goes on but the final conclusion is that regardless of what you do your pet will engage a mob eventually that you didn't intend it to.  And this is the danger of pets.  And from a damage per evening standpoint why not get the tank that does more damage and is smart damage absorption.  <P>Think about that before you dismiss pet control as a non issue.
</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
